{"title_page": "Hin Leong", "text_new": "'''Hin Leong Trading''' is a [[commodity trading]] corporation registered and headquartered in [[Singapore]] that was founded in 1963 by Lim Oon Kuin. One of Singapore's largest independent oil traders, Hin Leong filed for bankruptcy protection in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Forbes]]|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/lim-oon-kuin/#2299a8f856ca|title=Lim Oon Kuin|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nIn December 2010, Hin Leong announced plans to build Singapore's fourth oil refinery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/singapore-refinery/oil-trader-hin-leong-to-set-up-singapores-4th-refinery-idUSL3E6NM00B20101222|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|title=Oil trader Hin Leong to set up Singapore's 4th refinery|date=22 December 2010}}</ref> In 2014, the company announced plans to file for an [[initial public offering]] (IPO) but walked them back by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/energy-commodities/hin-leong-said-to-mull-universal-terminal-sale-after-ipo-pulled|title=Hin Leong said to mull Universal Terminal sale after IPO pulled|date=19 May 2015|newspaper=[[Business Times (Singapore)|Business Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==Bankruptcy==\nWhen the outbreak of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] in [[Wuhan]], China was first announced, Lim believed that the Chinese government would effectively contain it and therefore made the \"quintessential Hin Leong play\" of betting that oil prices would rise as a result of a recovering demand for oil.<ref name=st>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|title=How an epic gamble exposed the rot inside O.K. Lim's Hin Leong oil trading empire|date=21 April 2020|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/how-an-epic-gamble-exposed-the-rot-inside-o-k-lims-hin-leong-oil-trading}}</ref> However, as the coronavirus crisis worsened into a pandemic and amidst plunging crude oil prices, the company faced pressure to make partial loan repayments amounting to billions of dollars; despite selling off oil pledged as [[Collateral (finance)|collateral]], the company was still unable to raise enough money to pay down its loans. In a meeting with its lenders, Lim revealed that the company had written off $800 million in futures trading losses, although it had declared a revenue of $20 billion and a net income of close to $80 million in the 2019 financial year.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d812abf2-6e54-412c-9a2b-1ac3a1206219|title=Singapore scandal rocks commodity traders and lenders|date=21 April 2020|first1=Neil|last1=Hume|first2=Stefania|last2=Palma}}</ref><ref name=st/>\n\nThe company owed some $3.85 billion to 23 lenders, the biggest of which being [[HSBC]] which held $600 million of Hin Leong's debt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore oil traders face credit crunch after Hin Leong fiasco|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|date=22 April 2020|url=https://www.ft.com/content/03e17fdc-e966-451f-92b7-86707e8916a3}}</ref> Singapore's three largest banks also faced significant debt exposure to Hin Leong; [[United Overseas Bank|UOB]] was owed $100 million, whereas [[OCBC Bank|OCBC]] and [[DBS Bank]] had exposures of $200 million and $290 million respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/companies-markets/dbs-ocbc-uob-faced-with-over-us600m-total-exposure-to-hin-leong|title=DBS, OCBC, UOB faced with over US600m total exposure to Hin Leong|first=Marissa|last=Lee|date=17 April 2020|newspaper=[[Business Times (Singapore)|Business Times]]}}</ref> Having initially filed for bankruptcy protection under Section 211B of Singapore's Companies Act with the [[High Court of Singapore]] on 17 April 2020,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/debt-ridden-oil-trader-hin-leong-to-hand-control-to-pwc|title=Debt-ridden oil trader Hin Leong wants to hand control to PwC; Sembcorp unit cancels gasoil deal|date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Hin Leong subsequently sought for \"judicial management\" under independent accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC), which would oversee the restructuring of Hin Leong's debt.<ref name=st/><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|title=Scandal-hit Hin Leong seeks to cede control to PwC|first1=Neil|last1=Hume|first2=Stefania|last2=Palmia|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d726fe5e-a460-4fba-adba-a5bec21d8e01|date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLim resigned from Hin Leong on 17 April while stating that he wished for his children would remain as directors of the company.<ref name=st/> On 21 April, the [[Singapore Police Force]] confirmed that an investigation of Hin Leong was underway.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Channel News Asia]]|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/police-investigating-oil-trader-hin-leong-trading-12662052|title=Police investigating debt-laden oil trader Hin Leong Trading: What we know so far|last=Tang|first=See Kit|date=21 April 2020}}</ref> In a joint statement, the [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] (MAS), [[Enterprise Singapore]] (ESG) and the [[Maritime and Port Authority of Singapore]] (MPA) said that they were also \"closely monitoring developments related to the firm and the broader oil trading and bunkering sectors\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=22 April 2020|title=MAS, ACRA, MPA, Enterprise Singapore monitoring Hin Leong as police probe oil trading giant|last=Leong|first=Grace|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/mas-acra-mpa-enterprise-singspore-monitoring-hin-leong-as-police-probe}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Oil traders]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hin Leong Trading''' is a [[commodity trading]] corporation registered and headquartered in [[Singapore]] that was founded in 1963 by Lim Oon Kuin. One of Singapore's largest independent oil traders, Hin Leong fi