eong seeks to cede control to PwC|first1=Neil|last1=Hume|first2=Stefania|last2=Palmia|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d726fe5e-a460-4fba-adba-a5bec21d8e01|date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLim resigned from Hin Leong on 17 April while stating that he wished for his children would remain as directors of the company.<ref name=st/> On 21 April, the [[Singapore Police Force]] confirmed that an investigation of Hin Leong was underway.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Channel News Asia]]|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/police-investigating-oil-trader-hin-leong-trading-12662052|title=Police investigating debt-laden oil trader Hin Leong Trading: What we know so far|last=Tang|first=See Kit|date=21 April 2020}}</ref> In a joint statement, the [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] (MAS), [[Enterprise Singapore]] (ESG) and the [[Maritime and Port Authority of Singapore]] (MPA) said that they were also \"closely monitoring developments related to the firm and the broader oil trading and bunkering sectors\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=22 April 2020|title=MAS, ACRA, MPA, Enterprise Singapore monitoring Hin Leong as police probe oil trading giant|last=Leong|first=Grace|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/mas-acra-mpa-enterprise-singspore-monitoring-hin-leong-as-police-probe}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Oil traders]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Business Times\u2192Business Times (Singapore)(2),UOB\u2192United Overseas Bank,OCBC\u2192OCBC Bank", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hin_Leong"}
